      Elizabeth Holmes
   =20
 =20
In the early 2010s, Elizabeth Holmes pretended that she had invented a new =
technology to do blood tests, and used this pretend technology to raise sev=
eral hundred million dollars from gullible investors for her blood-testing =
startup, Theranos. Back in the 2010s this was all viewed as pretty notewort=
hy stuff, and it was huge news when Theranos=E2=80=99s technology turned ou=
t to be fake. We  talked about it a  bunch here at Money Stuff, and at some=
 point I coined a  pseudo-Linnaean name=C2=A0for Theranos,=C2=A0Elasmotheri=
um haimatos, the Blood Unicorn.=C2=A0Now of course it is 2022 and we are al=
l a bit more jaded. There was the SoftBank boom, we=E2=80=99ve had a couple=
 of years of SPACs, there is so much crypto. Raising hundreds of millions o=
f dollars from gullible investors who don=E2=80=99t do much due diligence i=
s not particularly impressive anymore. If you want to do it by pretending t=
o have a technology, you can (try  electric vehicles!), but these days even=
 that is optional. =E2=80=9CIn the past year, there has been a notable rush=
 of funding into the high-risk category of early-stage startups, as investo=
rs have clamored to get into companies even before they had a staff or prod=
uct,=E2=80=9D the Wall Street Journal reported on Sunday. Or you can raise =
lots of money from investors by letting them pretend to own digital picture=
s of apes, or by just saying =E2=80=9Chey here=E2=80=99s a Ponzi.=E2=80=9D =
Theranos raised a lot of money from investors who did not do too much due d=
iligence, because the world was awash in money and investors got careless; =
that is much, much, much, much more true now, and Theranos looks a little q=
uaint.But the gears of criminal prosecution grind slowly and yesterday Eliz=
abeth Holmes was  convicted of federal fraud charges:Holmes was convicted o=
f four out of 11 counts of conspiracy and wire fraud and acquitted of four =
counts. The jury didn=E2=80=99t reach a verdict on three of the counts. Hol=
mes was found not guilty of all charges pertaining to defrauding patients. =
=E2=80=A6After deliberating for seven full days, jurors agreed Monday with =
prosecutors that Holmes lied to investors over several years about the accu=
racy and capabilities of Theranos blood analyzers. A parade of witnesses to=
ld jurors they were gravely misled by the Stanford University dropout-turne=
d-entrepreneur. They ranged from executives at Walgreens and Safeway Inc. t=
o James Mattis, the former U.S. secretary of defense who served on the Ther=
anos board, as well as advisers to investors who poured hundreds of million=
s of dollars into the company.=C2=A0Part of  Holmes=E2=80=99s defense to th=
e charges of defrauding investors was that those investors did so little du=
e diligence that at some level they must have wanted to be defrauded. This =
defense did not work, and I am not sure it is a valid legal defense, but I =
sympathize. One of the charges on which she was convicted was defrauding Be=
tsy DeVos=E2=80=99s family office out of a $100 million investment. Lisa Pe=
terson, a DeVos family investment manager, testified at the trial:Lance Wad=
e, a lawyer for Ms. Holmes, asked Ms. Peterson, an investment professional,=
 if she was familiar with the concept of due diligence.=E2=80=9CYou underst=
and that=E2=80=99s a typical thing to do in investing?=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=A6Ms. Peterson testified that she was scared Ms. Holmes would cut he=
r firm out of the deal if they dug deeper into the details of Theranos=E2=
=80=99s business.=E2=80=9CWe were very careful not to circumvent things and=
 upset Elizabeth,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIf we did too much, we wouldn=
=E2=80=99t be invited back to invest.=E2=80=9DYeah I dunno if you make 10 i=
nvestments like that and one of them turns out to be a total fraud I think =
you say =E2=80=9Chey that went pretty well=E2=80=9D? Again, this was all so=
rt of an exciting novelty in the early 2010s but is old hat now. Here=E2=80=
=99s a Bloomberg News story from yesterday about =E2=80=9C What Investors L=
earned From the Elizabeth Holmes Trial: =E2=80=98Zero=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D:=E2=
=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think a verdict is going to change the way founders a=
nd VCs work in the ecosystem,=E2=80=9D said Angela Lee, who teaches venture=
 capital at Columbia Business School and runs 37 Angels, an investment netw=
ork that focuses on early-stage digital health companies. =E2=80=9CIt's abo=
ut supply and demand, and there's a tremendous capital supply with the same=
 number of awesome companies.=E2=80=9DWhen investors are competing to get i=
nto a round, one way they can edge out a rival is through speed. =E2=80=9CI=
 can't tell you how many times I hear, =E2=80=98So-and-so is in this deal, =
they're a name-brand VC, you have five days -- are you in or are you out?=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CPeople don't want to miss out. I am n=
ot seeing more thoughtful diligence. If anything, I=E2=80=99m actually seei=
ng a sped-up timeline for diligence in the last couple of years.=E2=80=9DLe=
e said the trial doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be prompting investors to re-exami=
ne their diligence practices. =E2=80=9CI've heard zero people say, =E2=80=
=98Oh, this should make me look differently,=E2=80=99 -- zero,=E2=80=9D she=
 said. =E2=80=9CIt's treated like salacious gossip or an entertaining story=
.=E2=80=9DAlso I think this is obviously the=C2=A0correct=C2=A0lesson for i=
nvestors to learn from Theranos? If the lesson you learned from Theranos=E2=
=80=99s fall in 2015, or 2018, was =E2=80=9CI am not going to invest in any=
 tech companies with charismatic founders and vague promises unless I=E2=80=
=99ve done thorough rigorous diligence, and if those founders object to tha=
t then they are not getting my money,=E2=80=9D then you have missed a lot o=
f good deals and the founders have not missed your money.[1] Betsy DeVos is=
 still rich despite blowing $100 million on Theranos, and lots of people wh=
o have casually rushed into fundraising rounds or SPACs or crypto Ponzis or=
 NFT drops or whatever in the last few years have done quite well.=C2=A0In =
a generally rising market where lots of fortunes are being made quickly, ru=
shing to back=C2=A0popular projects without a lot of due diligence seems to=
=C2=A0work, and if you back enough of them you=E2=80=99ll be fine even if a=
 few are frauds. The ones that work make you rich; the ones that are frauds=
 give you an entertaining story.It=E2=80=99s less entertaining for Holmes, =
who is heading for prison. It seems clear to me that one reason she was pro=
secuted while so many other fake-it-=E2=80=99til-you-make-it tech founders =
are not is that she was making fake=C2=A0blood tests=C2=A0and actually mark=
eting them to patients. =E2=80=9CBetsy DeVos lost $100 million on a failed =
startup=E2=80=9D is in a sense a less sympathetic story than =E2=80=9Csome =
regular person went to a drugstore, got an HIV test, and was falsely told t=
hat he was HIV-positive, upending his life.=E2=80=9D But Holmes was acquitt=
ed on the charges of defrauding patients; she was only convicted on (some o=
f) the charges of defrauding investors.There is I think an element of =E2=
=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D here. It turns out that there=
 is apparently not a federal crime of =E2=80=9Cgiving someone a fake diagno=
sis.=E2=80=9D Or, I mean, I guess there is, but it is the main all-purpose =
federal white-collar crime: It is =E2=80=9Cwire fraud.=E2=80=9D Telling som=
eone a lie for money is wire fraud.[2] If you tell someone =E2=80=9Chey I h=
ave invented a good blood test machine, want to invest?=E2=80=9D and they g=
ive you $100 million for stock, that=E2=80=99s wire fraud. If you tell some=
one =E2=80=9Chey I have invented a good blood test machine, want a blood te=
st?=E2=80=9D and they give you like $14.95 for a blood test, that=E2=80=99s=
 wire fraud.And so when Holmes was charged with wire fraud, it was for a mi=
x of investor fraud and patient fraud. =E2=80=9C Jurors heard Theranos pati=
ents testify their blood-test results falsely led them to believe they had =
unhealthy conditions,=E2=80=9D but found Holmes not guilty on those counts.=
=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know why =E2=80=94 I was not at the trial, and I cert=
ainly wasn=E2=80=99t in the jury room =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it seems plausible=
 that Holmes was less personally culpable for those tests than she was for =
her own pitches to investors. But never mind that.Instead, my point here is=
 that if you do a fake blood test on a patient, you have arguably defrauded=
 him (though Holmes was=C2=A0acquitted=C2=A0of that), but=C2=A0how much=C2=
=A0have you defrauded him really? Arguably the answer is quite a lot; argua=
bly he is quite badly harmed by thinking he had a deadly disease and taking=
 drastic steps to fight it, or thinking he did not have a deadly disease an=
d missing the chance to fight it. But arguably the answer is $14.95, or wha=
tever he paid for the blood test (I made that number up[3]): You were doing=
 fraud for money, and the money you got from any one patient is fairly smal=
l. Whereas the money you got from Betsy DeVos was $100 million.This is  a s=
tory I often tell: When a company harms some class of people in some bad bu=
t essentially non-monetary way, it is hard to quantify the damages as money=
; when a company harms its shareholders, you can just see how much the stoc=
k went down. (Theranos was never public but, uh, the stock went to zero.) O=
rdinarily this is a story about the incentives facing plaintiffs=E2=80=99 l=
awyers: If a company has a rampant culture of sexual harassment, it is much=
 more pleasant for plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers to bring a securities-fraud =
class action (=E2=80=9Cwhen the sexual-harassment news came out the stock w=
ent down=E2=80=9D) than it is for them to bring a sexual-harassment class a=
ction (=E2=80=9Ceach of these 1,000 employees were victims of a pattern of =
sexual harassment at your company=E2=80=9D), because the facts are neater a=
nd the plaintiffs more uniform and=C2=A0the damages much easier to prove an=
d probably larger.But this is true for prosecutors bringing wire-fraud char=
ges too. Prosecutors do not want to bring a federal criminal case against s=
omeone who defrauded a victim out of $14.95. Even someone who defrauded 1,0=
00 victims out of $14.95 each is tough; you have to prove the facts about e=
ach victim. Even if the fraud also involved giving those victims scary and =
harmful medical misdiagnoses.=C2=A0This is partly just a matter of putting =
big numbers in the press release, and it=E2=80=99s partly a matter of what=
=E2=80=99s easier to prove =E2=80=94=C2=A0remember the jury acquitted Holme=
s of the patient charges =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s also a matter of=C2=A0s=
entencing. Prosecutors want to bring big cases that get long prison sentenc=
es. There are=C2=A0various factors that go into a prison sentence for wire =
fraud, but by far the most important one is the amount of money involved.[4=
]=C2=A0A $100 million fraud will get a long sentence. A small-money=C2=A0fr=
aud on retail purchasers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even one with hundreds of victims =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0even one where the victims suffered not so much the out-of-p=
ocket cost of a blood test but rather the emotional and medical problems of=
 a bad test result =E2=80=94=C2=A0will not amount to much money and so will=
 tend to get a shorter sentence. If the main all-purpose federal crime is w=
ire fraud, then the law will focus on the biggest wire frauds, and the bigg=
est wire frauds, measured by money, tend to be the ones against shareholder=
s.
