   =20
      Pro-ESG
   =20
 =20
Speaking of BlackRock Inc. saving the world on your behalf, BlackRock Chief=
 Executive Officer Larry Fink said recently about its ESG efforts=C2=A0that=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CBlackRock is a leader in this, and we are seeing the flows, =
and I continue to see this big shift in investor portfolios.=E2=80=9D But  =
Bloomberg News=C2=A0notes:What Fink did not say is that BlackRock drove a s=
ignificant part of that shift by inserting its primary ESG fund into popula=
r and influential model portfolios offered to investment advisers, who use =
them with clients across North America. The huge flows from such models mea=
n many investors got into an ESG vehicle without necessarily choosing one a=
s a specific investment strategy, or even knowing that their money has gone=
 into one.In short, an apparent BlackRock-led rush of investors into ESG in=
 the past two years has been something of a self-fulfilling prophecy, at le=
ast when it comes to the biggest such fund on the planet, a BlackRock excha=
nge-traded fund that trades under the ticker symbol ESGU, according to data=
 from BlackRock and Morningstar. ...On Jan. 15, 2020, the day after Fink=E2=
=80=99s letter predicted a major reallocation of capital into sustainabilit=
y, BlackRock altered its most popular suite of model portfolios by adding E=
SGU into its =E2=80=9CTarget Allocation ETF Portfolio Strategies=E2=80=9D s=
eries. (The biggest and most popular one inside the suite, which offers a 6=
0/40 split between stocks and fixed income investments, includes ESGU as on=
e of its top two holdings.)In this way, BlackRock itself helped assure Fink=
=E2=80=99s prediction would come true. Financial planners who use the model=
s through online platforms have had no choice but to put their clients in E=
SGU if they wanted to get them into one of the most popular investment stra=
tegies for sale.This seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0obviously good? The problem, for =
BlackRock, is that it is largely in the business of selling index funds. It=
 has a big S&P 500 index fund, and if a stock is in the S&P 500 index then =
BlackRock has to own that stock, and if that stock is a coal company then, =
you know, oops. BlackRock can go to the coal company and say =E2=80=9Cwe ar=
e a 5% shareholder of your company and we want you to mine less coal,=E2=80=
=9D but (1) that is pretty self-defeating and (2) if the company says no, w=
hat can BlackRock=C2=A0do,=C2=A0sell its stock? And so Larry Fink sends out=
 letters about how companies should do better at ESG, but his funds mostly =
don=E2=80=99t get to pick what stocks they buy, so they end up owning lots =
of stocks that are bad at ESG.But Fink does get to pick, within limits,=C2=
=A0what funds his investors buy. If you change the model portfolio=E2=80=99=
s main stock allocation from the S&P 500 to an ESG fund, and your clients b=
lithely go along, then you will find yourself buying more good ESG stocks a=
nd fewer bad ESG stocks while still basically offering index funds. As a fu=
nd manager=C2=A0you are largely passive, but as a=C2=A0marketer of funds=C2=
=A0you get to do quite a lot of active allocation. The people buying your p=
assive funds are not, after all, deeply engaged connoisseurs of the stock m=
arket; they=E2=80=99re buying a model portfolio of passive BlackRock funds =
because they don't want to think too hard about stocks. Might as well put t=
he stocks=C2=A0you like in there!When BlackRock first announced its plans t=
o do this back in 2020,  I wrote:The right model of BlackRock is probably t=
hat it is mostly an aggregator of preferences, but it is also, at the margi=
n, a shaper of preferences.=C2=A0It passively reflects what investors want =
generally, but it has some ability to push those investors to want differen=
t things. There are other things that BlackRock does=E2=80=94it votes the s=
hares of stock that it owns on behalf of investors, it meets with managers =
to talk about their sustainability plans, it writes strongly worded letters=
 to CEOs=E2=80=94but I suspect that they=E2=80=99re mostly less important t=
han the basic core function of taking $7 trillion from investors, channelin=
g it where the investors want it to go, and slowly and subtly diverting tho=
se channels so that the money moves=C2=A0more in the direction that=C2=A0Bl=
ackRock=C2=A0wants it to go.=C2=A0Obviously if you think that BlackRock=E2=
=80=99s goals are bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance if you think that ESG in =
general, or BlackRock=E2=80=99s implementation of it in particular, is a sc=
am =E2=80=94=C2=A0then this seems bad. But if you are Larry Fink and you=C2=
=A0genuinely believe that ESG investing can make the world better, then thi=
s is the best possible outcome. Abandoning broad index investing to be ESG-=
only will lose you customers, abandoning ESG to serve your broad index cust=
omers will be bad for the world, but gently nudging your index customers in=
to ESG indexes will let you do good while doing well. Also of course the fe=
es are higher:ESGU=E2=80=99s fees are lower than industry averages for sust=
ainable funds but are still five times higher than an S&P 500 tracker that =
trades under the ticker IVV =C2=A0-- a popular BlackRock fund whose makeup =
and expected performance are closely aligned with those of ESGU.
