      Can=E2=80=99t believe Ken Griffin is going to buy Blockbuster now
   =20
 =20
Yeah I mean sure of course right:Just weeks after a decentralized autonomou=
s organization (DAO) tried to buy an original copy of the US Constitution, =
another historical artifact has become the target of a DAO: the defunct mov=
ie rental business Blockbuster.=C2=A0The new DAO=E2=80=99s name is, aptly, =
BlockbusterDAO. According to a Twitter thread posted on December 25, Blockb=
usterDAO seeks to govern the Blockbuster brand and create a decentralized f=
ilm streaming service out of it =E2=80=94 with plans for movie financing an=
d production down the road.=C2=A0To achieve its goals, BlockbusterDAO inten=
ds to raise $5 million to purchase Blockbuster from Dish Network, an Americ=
an television provider that bought the movie rental company in 2011. Blockb=
usterDAO aims to raise the cash by selling BlockbusterDAO NFTs for 0.13 ETH=
 (about $530 USD).=C2=A0We  talked last month about some guys who bought Ra=
dioShack out of bankruptcy to pivot it to crypto, and this follows a simila=
r playbook. You take the basic bones of the GameStop situation (nostalgic b=
rand, physical stores rendered obsolete by streaming, vague plans for digit=
al pivot), you sprinkle some crypto over it (it's a DAO, it's going to be =
=E2=80=9Cthe first-ever DeFilm streaming platform=E2=80=9D), and, boom, you=
=E2=80=99ve got a thing.Here in particular there are endless possible vehic=
les for speculation, as the BlockbusterDAO Twitter account lays out:Allow B=
lockHead staking to collect BlockBuster Rewards. =E2=80=A6 It will be impor=
tant to start building out rewards for DAO participation and community even=
ts. ...Develop a Blockbuster NFT presence and use proceeds to fund developm=
ent. ...We can create a =E2=80=9CMovie Pass=E2=80=9D subscription model for=
 our plaform, making those passes ERC-20 tokens that have resale value.Etc.=
 Just turn every part of the experience into its own speculative asset. Wil=
l this be a better way to watch movies? I mean, I dunno, probably not as an=
 aesthetic experience or anything, but sure yes probably =E2=80=9Cwatching =
movies and also somehow getting paid a million dollars for it=E2=80=9D does=
 seem superior to =E2=80=9Cwatching movies and paying for it.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0We  talked last month about Web3, the new name for crypto-based internet=
 services. =E2=80=9CA basic premise of Web3 is that every product is simult=
aneously an investment opportunity,=E2=80=9D I wrote:It=E2=80=99s as if bei=
ng an early user of Facebook or Uber also automatically made you a=C2=A0sha=
reholder=C2=A0of Facebook or Uber, and when those services got huge you got=
 rich. ...What sort of incentives does this create to spend your time makin=
g good products? Not none! But =E2=80=A6 attenuated, no? If you could spend=
 a day optimizing the color scheme and messaging mechanics of your social n=
etwork, or instead optimizing the payoff structure of the tokens, which one=
 creates more value? If every product is also an investment, will the produ=
ct engineers be mostly financial engineers?The pitch here is not, you know,=
 about the technical skills of the people building the DeFilm streaming pla=
tform, or about their aesthetic judgment in movies, or even about their mar=
keting skills. The pitch here is that there are a bunch of speculative asse=
ts, because that is what Web3 is.
