      Bank error in your favor
   =20
 =20
I don=E2=80=99t know man:Santander UK is trying to recover about $175 milli=
on, or about 130 million pounds, that it accidentally paid tens of thousand=
s of people on Christmas Day.About 75,000 people received the mistaken paym=
ents, including many customers of rival banks. Santander is seeking help fr=
om the other banks to recoup the money, the bank said in a statement.The mi=
staken deposits could look like normal payments to recipients because they =
were duplicates of regular and one-off payments that about 2,000 of the ban=
k=E2=80=99s commercial and corporate customers had already paid to people i=
ncluding their suppliers and employees.Santander said the money for those s=
econd payments did not come from its customers. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Santander UK=
, the British arm of Banco Santander of Spain, has more than 14.4 million c=
ustomers. The British operation reported profits of about $929 million (=C2=
=A3687 million) before taxes in the third quarter of this year, up from =C2=
=A3151 million in the same period in 2020.I am not going to give anyone any=
 legal or financial advice here but I feel like if you=E2=80=99re a big pro=
fitable bank and you wake up on Boxing Day to find out that you accidentall=
y handed out $175 million of Christmas presents to your customers=E2=80=99 =
payees, you have two options.=09You can say =E2=80=9Coops sorry about that,=
=E2=80=9D Grinchily try to get the money back, end up suing some people who=
 spent it, and explain to your regulators why you can=E2=80=99t do the esse=
ntial banking task of keeping track of the money.=09Or! Or, you can put out=
 a press release that=C2=A0is like =E2=80=9CSantander UK just gave out $175=
 million in Christmas presents to thousands of people, because we care, San=
tander, the bank that cares or whatever.=E2=80=9D And then everyone is like=
 =E2=80=9Cwow what a good bank=E2=80=9D and opens a credit card with you.Do=
es Option 2 buy you $175 million worth of good publicity? Probably not, ver=
sus a baseline of not doing any of this. But does it save you $175 million =
of aggravation, versus Option 1? Maybe? I guess the problem with Option 2 i=
s your regulators are not going to believe it, and you=E2=80=99re going to =
have to explain both=C2=A0why you couldn't keep track of the money and=C2=
=A0why you covered it up by pretending you meant to do it.
