kground-color: #ccc;">reported</a> on Sunday. Or you can raise lots of mone=
y from investors by letting them pretend to own digital pictures of apes, o=
r by just saying =E2=80=9Chey here=E2=80=99s a Ponzi.=E2=80=9D Theranos rai=
sed a lot of money from investors who did not do too much due diligence, be=
cause the world was awash in money and investors got careless; that is much=
, much, much, much more true now, and Theranos looks a little quaint.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the gears of criminal prosecution grind slow=
ly and yesterday Elizabeth Holmes was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
zL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMDMvaG9sbWVzLWp1cm9ycy1zYXktc3RydWdnbGluZy10by1yZW=
FjaC12ZXJkaWN0LW9uLTMtb2YtMTEtY291bnRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEwNCZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb3afac78" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 convicted of federal fraud charges</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Holmes was convicted of four out of 11 counts of conspiracy and w=
ire fraud and acquitted of four counts. The jury didn=E2=80=99t reach a ver=
dict on three of the counts. Holmes was found not guilty of all charges per=
taining to defrauding patients. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
fter deliberating for seven full days, jurors agreed Monday with prosecutor=
s that Holmes lied to investors over several years about the accuracy and c=
apabilities of Theranos blood analyzers. A parade of witnesses told jurors =
they were gravely misled by the Stanford University dropout-turned-entrepre=
neur. They ranged from executives at Walgreens and Safeway Inc. to James Ma=
ttis, the former U.S. secretary of defense who served on the Theranos board=
, as well as advisers to investors who poured hundreds of millions of dolla=
rs into the company.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Par=
t of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.2776=
59/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDgv=
ZWxvbi1tdXNrLWRpZC1zb21lLXR3ZWV0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMDQmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBef157df3" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Holme=
s=E2=80=99s defense</a> to the charges of defrauding investors was that tho=
se investors did so little due diligence that at some level they must have =
wanted to be defrauded. This defense did not work, and I am not sure it is =
a valid legal defense, but I sympathize. One of the charges on which she wa=
s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/=
aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9lcmluZ3JpZmZpdGgvc3RhdHVzLzE0NzgxNjEwODg3Mzg4NDg=
3NzQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30aab9d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">convicted</a> was defraudin=
g Betsy DeVos=E2=80=99s family office out of a <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb2=
0vMjAyMi8wMS8wMy90ZWNobm9sb2d5L2VsaXphYmV0aC1ob2xtZXMtZ3VpbHR5Lmh0bWw/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBca069e75" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">$100 million</a> investment. Lisa Pet=
erson, a DeVos family investment manager, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjA=
yMS8xMS8wNC90ZWNobm9sb2d5L3RoZXJhbm9zLWVsaXphYmV0aC1ob2xtZXMtaW52ZXN0b3JzLW=
RpbGlnZW5jZS5odG1sP3NtdHlwPWN1ciZzbWlkPXR3LW55dGltZXNidXNpbmVzcw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBe9817776" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">testified at the trial</a>:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lance Wade, a lawyer for Ms. Holmes, asked Ms=
. Peterson, an investment professional, if she was familiar with the concep=
t of due diligence.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou understand=
 that=E2=80=99s a typical thing to do in investing?=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ms. Peterson testified that she was =
scared Ms. Holmes would cut her firm out of the deal if they dug deeper int=
o the details of Theranos=E2=80=99s business.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">=E2=80=9CWe were very careful not to circumvent things and upset Elizabe=
th,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIf we did too much, we wouldn=E2=80=99t be =
invited back to invest.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Yeah I dunno if you make 10 investments like that and one of them turns =
out to be a total fraud I think you say =E2=80=9Chey that went pretty well=
=E2=80=9D? Again, this was all sort of an exciting novelty in the early 201=
0s but is old hat now. Here=E2=80=99s a Bloomberg News story from yesterday=
 about =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26=
253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItM=
DEtMDQvd2hhdC1pbnZlc3RvcnMtbGVhcm5lZC1mcm9tLXRoZS1lbGl6YWJldGgtaG9sbWVzLXRy=
aWFsLXplcm8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEwNDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBebaa6913" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> What Investors Learned From =
the Elizabeth Holmes Trial: =E2=80=98Zero=E2=80=99</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think a verdict =
is going to change the way founders and VCs work in the ecosystem,=E2=80=9D=
 said Angela Lee, who teaches venture capital at Columbia Business School a=
nd runs 37 Angels, an investment network that focuses on early-stage digita=
l health companies. =E2=80=9CIt's about supply and demand, and there's a tr=
emendous capital supply with the same number of awesome companies.=E2=80=9D=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When investors are competing to get into a=
 round, one way they can edge out a rival is through speed. =E2=80=9CI can'=
t tell you how many times I hear, =E2=80=98So-and-so is in this deal, they'=
re a name-brand VC, you have five days -- are you in or are you out?=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CPeople don't want to miss out. I am not see=
ing more thoughtful diligence. If anything, I=E2=80=99m actually seeing a s=
ped-up timeline for diligence in the last couple of years.=E2=80=9D</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lee said the trial doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be prom=
pting investors to re-examine their diligence practices. =E2=80=9CI've hear=
d zero people say, =E2=80=98Oh, this should make me look differently,=E2=80=
=99 -- zero,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIt's treated like salacious gossip=
 or an entertaining story.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Also I think this is obviously the=C2=A0<em>correct=C2=A0</em>lesson =
for investors to learn from Theranos? If the lesson you learned from Theran=
os=E2=80=99s fall in 2015, or 2018, was =E2=80=9CI am not going to invest i=
n any tech companies with charismatic founders and vague promises unless I=
=E2=80=99ve done thorough rigorous diligence, and if those founders object =
to that then they are not getting my money,=E2=80=9D then you have missed a=
 lot of good deals and the founders have not missed your money.[1] Betsy De=
Vos is still rich despite blowing $100 million on Theranos, and lots of peo=
ple who have casually rushed into fundraising rounds or SPACs or crypto Pon=
zis or NFT drops or whatever in the last few years have done quite well.=C2=
=A0In a generally rising market where lots of fortunes are being made quick=
ly, rushing to back=C2=A0popular projects without a lot of due diligence se=
ems to=C2=A0<em>work</em>, and if you back enough of them you=E2=80=99ll be=
 fine even if a few are frauds. The ones that work make you rich; the ones =
that are frauds give you an entertaining story.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">It=E2=80=99s less entertaining for Holmes, who is heading for prison. =
It seems clear to me that one reason she was prosecuted while so many other=
 fake-it-=E2=80=99til-you-make-it tech founders are not is that she was mak=
ing fake=C2=A0<em>blood tests=C2=A0</em>and actually marketing them to pati=
ents. =E2=80=9CBetsy DeVos lost $100 million on a failed startup=E2=80=9D i=
s in a sense a less sympathetic story than =E2=80=9Csome regular person wen=
t to a drugstore, got an HIV test, and was falsely told that he was HIV-pos=
itive, upending his life.=E2=80=9D But Holmes was acquitted on the charges =
of defrauding patients; she was only convicted on (some of) the charges of =
defrauding investors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is I think an e=
lement of =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/26253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZ=
HMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEwNCZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3a36063" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">ever=
ything is securities fraud</a>=E2=80=9D here. It turns out that there is ap=
parently not a federal crime of =E2=80=9Cgiving someone a fake diagnosis.=
=E2=80=9D Or, I mean, I guess there is, but it is the main all-purpose fede=
ral white-collar crime: It is =E2=80=9Cwire fraud.=E2=80=9D Telling someone=
 a lie for money is wire fraud.[2] If you tell someone =E2=80=9Chey I have =
invented a good blood test machine, want to invest?=E2=80=9D and they give =
you $100 million for stock, that=E2=80=99s wire fraud. If you tell someone =
=E2=80=9Chey I have invented a good blood test machine, want a blood test?=
=E2=80=9D and they give you like $14.95 for a blood test, that=E2=80=99s wi=
re fraud.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so when Holmes was charged wi=
th wire fraud, it was for a mix of investor fraud and patient fraud. =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMDMvaG9sbW=
VzLWp1cm9ycy1zYXktc3RydWdnbGluZy10by1yZWFjaC12ZXJkaWN0LW9uLTMtb2YtMTEtY291b=
nRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJj=
ZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb3afac78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Jurors heard</a> Theranos patients =
testify their blood-test results falsely led them to believe they had unhea=
lthy conditions,=E2=80=9D but found Holmes not guilty on those counts.=C2=
=A0I don=E2=80=99t know why =E2=80=94 I was not at the trial, and I certain=
ly wasn=E2=80=99t in the jury room =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it seems plausible th=
at Holmes was less personally culpable for those tests than she was for her=
 own pitches to investors. But never mind that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Instead, my point here is that if you do a fake blood test on a patien=
t, you have arguably defrauded him (though Holmes was=C2=A0<em>acquitted=C2=
=A0</em>of that), but=C2=A0<em>how much=C2=A0</em>have you defrauded him re=
ally? Arguably the answer is quite a lot; arguably he is quite badly harmed=
 by thinking he had a deadly disease and taking drastic steps to fight it, =
or thinking he did not have a deadly disease and missing the chance to figh=
t it. But arguably the answer is $14.95, or whatever he paid for the blood =
test (I made that number up[3]): You were doing fraud for money, and the mo=
ney you got from any one patient is fairly small. Whereas the money you got=
 from Betsy DeVos was $100 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDUvZHlz=
dG9waWFuLWZ1dHVyZS1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEwNC=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1058ed36" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> a story I often tell</a>: When a company harms some class of people in so=
me bad but essentially non-monetary way, it is hard to quantify the damages=
 as money; when a company harms its shareholders, you can just see how much=
 the stock went down. (Theranos was never public but, uh, <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26253475.277659/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMDUvdGhlLWJsb29kLXVuaWNvcm=
4taXMtZXh0aW5jdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCf54a50ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the stock went to zero</=
a>.) Ordinarily this is a story about the incentives facing plaintiffs=E2=
=80=99 lawyers: If a company has a rampant culture of sexual harassment, it=
 is much more pleasant for plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers to bring a securitie=
s-fraud class action (=E2=80=9Cwhen the sexual-harassment news came out the=
 stock went down=E2=80=9D) than it is for them to bring a sexual-harassment=
 class action (=E2=80=9Ceach of these 1,000 employees were victims of a pat=
tern of sexual harassment at your company=E2=80=9D), because the facts are =
neater and the plaintiffs more uniform and=C2=A0the damages much easier to =
prove and probably larger.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is true=
 for prosecutors bringing wire-fraud charges too. Prosecutors do not want t=
o bring a federal criminal case against someone who defrauded a victim out =
of $14.95. Even someone who defrauded 1,000 victims out of $14.95 each is t=
ough; you have to prove the facts about each victim. Even if the fraud also=
 involved giving those victims scary and harmful medical misdiagnoses.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is partly just a matter of putting=
 big numbers in the press release, and it=E2=80=99s partly a matter of what=
=E2=80=99s easier to prove =E2=80=94=C2=A0remember the jury acquitted Holme=
s of the patient charges =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s also a matter of=C2=A0<=
em>sentencing</em>. Prosecutors want to bring big cases that get long priso=
n sentences. There are=C2=A0various factors that go into a prison sentence =
for wire fraud, but by far the most important one is the amount of money in=
volved.[4]=C2=A0A $100 million fraud will get a long sentence. A small-mone=
y=C2=A0fraud on retail purchasers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even one with hundreds of =
victims =E2=80=94=C2=A0even one where the victims suffered not so much the =
out-of-pocket cost of a blood test but rather the emotional and medical pro=
blems of a bad test result =E2=80=94=C2=A0will not amount to much money and=
 so will tend to get a shorter sentence. If the main all-purpose federal cr=
ime is wire fraud, then the law will focus on the biggest wire frauds, and =
the biggest wire frauds, measured by money, tend to be the ones against sha=
reholders.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" =
