ccc;"> I wrote</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The right m=
odel of BlackRock is probably that it is mostly an aggregator of preference=
s, but it is also, at the margin, a shaper of preferences.=C2=A0It passivel=
y reflects what investors want generally, but it has some ability to push t=
hose investors to want different things. There are other things that BlackR=
ock does=E2=80=94it votes the shares of stock that it owns on behalf of inv=
estors, it meets with managers to talk about their sustainability plans, it=
 writes strongly worded letters to CEOs=E2=80=94but I suspect that they=E2=
=80=99re mostly less important than the basic core function of taking $7 tr=
illion from investors, channeling it where the investors want it to go, and=
 slowly and subtly diverting those channels so that the money moves=C2=A0mo=
re in the direction that=C2=A0<em>BlackRock=C2=A0</em>wants it to go.=C2=A0=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously if you think that B=
lackRock=E2=80=99s goals are bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance if you think t=
hat ESG in general, or BlackRock=E2=80=99s implementation of it in particul=
ar, is a scam =E2=80=94=C2=A0then this seems bad. But if you are Larry Fink=
 and you=C2=A0<em>genuinely believe that ESG investing can make the world b=
etter</em>, then this is the best possible outcome. Abandoning broad index =
investing to be ESG-only will lose you customers, abandoning ESG to serve y=
our broad index customers will be bad for the world, but gently nudging you=
r index customers into ESG indexes will let you do good while doing well. A=
lso of course the fees are higher:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">ESGU=E2=80=99s fees are lower than industry averages for sustainable fu=
nds but are still five times higher than an S&amp;P 500 tracker that trades=
